Erich von Brückner ( 1896 - -1949 ) was a German officer of the Brandenburgers during World War II . He was awarded the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross on 11 March 1945 .

On the same day , President Barack Obama announced that Ride would receive the Presidential Medal of Freedom , the highest civilian award in the United States .
Luther Skaggs , Jr. ( March 3 , 1923 -- April 6 , 1976 ) was a United States Marine who received the Medal of Honor for his heroic actions on the beachhead on Guam during World War II .
Morris Brown , Jr. ( August , 1842 - June 22 , 1864 ) was an American soldier who received the Medal of Honor for valor during the American Civil War .

Commander Norman Douglas Holbrook VC ( 9 July 1888 -- 3 July 1976 ) was a British naval recipient of the Victoria Cross ( VC ) , the highest award of the British honours system .

Stefanía Fernández Krupij ( born September 4 , 1990 ) is a Venezuelan TV Host , model and beauty queen who won the Miss Venezuela 2008 and Miss Universe 2009 titles .

Vinzenz Kaiser ( 28 February 1904 -- 20 April 1945 ) was an Obersturmbannführer ( Lieutenant Colonel ) in the Waffen SS during World War II . He was a recipient of the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross , awarded to recognize extreme battlefield bravery or successful military leadership by Nazi Germany during World War II .
Rakesh Sharma , AC , Hero of the Soviet Union , ( born 13 January 1949 ) is a former Indian Air Force pilot who flew aboard Soyuz T-11 , launched April 3 , 1984 , as part of the Intercosmos programme .

Hugh McInnes VC ( October 1815 -- 7 December 1879 ) was a Scottish recipient of the Victoria Cross .

Benjamin F. Stewart ( born 1851 ) was a Private in the United States Army who received the Medal of Honor for his actions during the Indian Wars .

It starred Fanfreluche , a living doll ( played by Kim Yaroshevskaya ) who retold fairy tales and legends to the viewers .
30 Rock is an American satirical television sitcom created by Tina Fey that ran on NBC from October 11 , 2006 to January 31 , 2013 .
Towards Zero is a work of detective fiction by Agatha Christie first published in the US by Dodd , Mead and Company in June 1944 , selling for $ 2.00 , and in the UK by the Collins Crime Club in July of the same year .
Equivalents is a series of photographs of clouds taken by Alfred Stieglitz from 1925 to 1934 .
The Semi - Gods Ceiling is a painting work by Italian Renaissance master Pinturicchio , dating to c. 1490 and housed in the right wing hall of the Palazzo dei Penitenzieri in Rome , Italy .
Snooper and Blabber is one of the sequences from The Quick Draw McGraw Show ( produced by Hanna - Barbera , between 1959 and 1962 ) .
Vir Heroicus Sublimis is a painting by Barnett Newman , an American painter who was a key part of the abstract expressionist movement .
Napoleon in the Wilderness is a 1941 surrealist painting by Max Ernst in the collection of the Museum of Modern Art .
Coucher de soleil no . 1 ( also called Landscape , Paysage , Landschap , or Sunset No . 1 ) is an oil painting created circa 1906 by the French artist and theorist Jean Metzinger ( 1883 - -1956 ) .
The Dream and Lie of Franco is a series of two sheets of prints , comprising 18 individual images , and an accompanying prose poem , by Pablo Picasso produced in 1937 .
Hokey Wolf is a Hanna - Barbera cartoon about the adventures of a con - artist wolf who is always trying to cheat his way into the simple life .
Dispositif is a term used by the French intellectual Michel Foucault , generally to refer to the various institutional , physical , and administrative mechanisms and knowledge structures which enhance and maintain the exercise of power within the social body .
Druuna is an erotic science fiction and fantasy comic book character created by Italian cartoonist Paolo Eleuteri Serpieri .
Aquis Submersus ( Latin for Water Drowning ) is a painting by the German dadaist and surrealist Max Ernst created in 1919 .
Bone Chillers is a series of children 's horror fiction novels and TV show created and authored by Betsy Haynes .
The Bamberg Horseman ( German : Der Bamberger Reiter ) is a life - size stone equestrian statue by an anonymous medieval sculptor in the cathedral of Bamberg , Germany .
The Edith Cavell Memorial is an outdoor memorial to Edith Cavell by Sir George Frampton , in London , United Kingdom .
Il Quadrato di Villafranca or Esercitazione di tiro is a painting by Giovanni Fattori created in 1876 - -1880 depicting a scene of the Battle of Custoza ( 1866 ) .
Allegory of Waterloo , also known as Triumph of the Duke of Wellington or the Triumph of Great Britain after the Battle of Waterloo , was a monumental painting by British artist James Ward , completed in 1821 , and now lost .
Morphological Echo is a title shared by two oil on panel paintings created by the Spanish surrealist Salvador Dalí .
Two Open Rectangles , Excentric , Variation VI , is a public artwork by American artist George Rickey , located on the Middlebury College campus , outside of the Christian A. Johnson Memorial Building , in Middlebury , Vermont , United States .
Emmanuel Goldstein is a character in George Orwell 's dystopian novel Nineteen Eighty - Four .
Sitting Ducks is a lithograph created by the poster artist Michael Bedard in the late 1970s .
Portrait of a Musician is an oil on wood painting attributed to Leonardo da Vinci by some scholars .
Cromwell on his Farm ( 1874 ) is a painting by Ford Madox Brown which depicts Oliver Cromwell observing a bonfire on his farm and thinking of a passage in the Book of Psalms : `` Lord , how long wilt thy hide thyself - forever ?
The Death of Leonardo da Vinci is an 1818 painting by the French artist Jean Auguste Dominique Ingres , showing the painter Leonardo da Vinci dying , with Francis I of France holding his head .
The Regents of the Old Men 's Almshouse is a regents ' group portrait of five regents and their servant painted by Frans Hals in 1664 for the Oude Mannenhuis in Haarlem , the Netherlands .
Oi Yoi Yoi is a 1963 oil painting by British painter Roger Hilton .
The New Adventures of Old Christine was created and produced by Kari Lizer as well as Andy Ackerman ( who directed all 88 episodes of the series ) , and distributed by Warner Bros. Television .
A Charlie Brown Celebration is the 23rd prime - time animated TV special based upon the popular comic strip Peanuts , by Charles M. Schulz , who introduced the hour - long special .
Bal du moulin de la Galette ( commonly known as Dance at Le moulin de la Galette ) is an 1876 painting by French artist Pierre - Auguste Renoir .
Bhamidipati Radhakrishna ( 1929 -- September 4 , 2007 ) was an Indian playwright and script writer in Telugu cinema .
Prince Moulay Ismail of Morocco ( born 7 May 1981 ) is the son of Prince Moulay Abdallah and Lalla Lamia Solh .
Basil Feilding , 4th Earl of Denbigh , 3rd Earl of Desmond ( 1668 -- 18 March 1717 ) was a British peer and member of the House of Lords , styled Viscount Feilding from 1675 to 1685 .
Charles Aitken CB ( 12 September 1869 -- 9 August 1936 ) was a British art administrator and was the third Keeper of the Tate Gallery ( 1911 - -1917 ) and the first Director ( 1917 - -1930 ) .
Terry Biddlecombe ( 2 February 1941 -- 5 January 2014 ) was an English National Hunt racing jockey in the 1960s and 1970s .
Chambré Brabazon Ponsonby ( c. 1720 -- 20 February 1762 ) was an Irish Member of Parliament .
Eric Roll , Baron Roll of Ipsden KCMG CB ( 1 December 1907 -- 30 March 2005 ) was an academic economist , public servant and banker .
Joy Shelton ( 3 June 1922 -- 28 January 2000 ) was an English actress who performed in films , radio and television .
Christopher Beeston ( c. 1579 -- c. 15 October 1638 ) was a successful actor and a powerful theatrical impresario in early 17th century London .
Ernst Sören Nordin ( 5 September 1917 , Forsa , Hälsingland -- 6 September 2008 ) was a Swedish harness racing driver and trainer who later started a stable in America .
Diarmait mac Tommaltaig ( died 833 ) was a king of Connacht from the Uí Briúin branch of the Connachta .
Jan Cockx ( 1891 , Boechout -- 26 August 1976 ) was a Belgian painter perhaps best known for landscapes , still life and harbor scenes .
Sebastijan Pečjak ( died 6 July 2012 ) was a Slovenian darts player who was most notable for representing Slovenia at the 2010 PDC World Cup of Darts along with team mate Osmann Kijamet .
Robert Morris Page ( 2 June 1903 -- 15 May 1992 ) was an American physicist who was a leading figure in the development of radar technology .
Claud Farie , sometimes spelled Claude Farie ( 5 December 1816 -- 22 August 1870 ) was sheriff and politician in colonial Victoria , a member of the Victorian Legislative Council .
Madern Gerthener ( 1360/1370 -- 1430 ) was a German stonemason and late Gothic architect .
Lewis Wormser Harris ( 1812 - 1876 ) was a bill - broker , financier , member of Dublin Corporation ( elected Lord Mayor ) and prominent member of the Dublin Hebrew Congregation .
Rosemary Adey , OAM ( 29 January 1933 -- 1 October 2013 ) was an Australian softball player and sports administrator .
Arnold Walfisz ( 2 July 1892 -- 29 May 1962 ) was a Polish mathematician working in analytic number theory .
Jesús García Leoz ( Olite , Navarra , 10 January 1904 -- 1953 ) was a Spanish composer , particularly noted for his film scores .
Matilda Heming , née Lowry ( 1796 -- 1855 ) was a British painter .
Giovanna Daffini ( 22 April 1914 -- 7 July 1969 ) was an Italian singer , associated with the Nuovo Canzoniere Italiano movement .
Marianne Rauze ( 20 September 1875 -- 23 October 1964 ) was a French journalist , feminist , socialist , pacifist and communist .
Eily Malyon ( 30 October 1879 -- 26 September 1961 ) was an English character actress in the 1930s and 1940s .
Robert Caird FRSE LLD ( died 1 December 1915 in Greenock ) , was a Scottish shipbuilder .
After a long battle with acute myelogenous leukemia ( AML ) , Keith Parkinson died on 26 October 2005 .
Anushirwan Khan ( Persian : انوشیروان خان‎ , Anūshīrvān Khān ) occupied the Ilkhanid throne from 1344 until his death in 1357 .
Dionysius Lardner ( 3 April 1793 -- 29 April 1859 ) was an Irish scientific writer who popularised science and technology , and edited the 133-volume Cabinet Cyclopædia .
David Willis Wilson Henderson CB FRS ( 23 July 1903 -- 16 August 1968 ) was a Scottish - born microbiologist ; a former President of the Society for General Microbiology and recipient of the U.S. Medal of Freedom .
Dr. Thomas Chalmers Robertson ( 15 September 1907 - 11 January 1989 ) was an author , ecologist and conservationist from South Africa .
Charlotta Öberg ( Stockholm , 1818 -- 21 June 1856 ) known as Lotta Öberg , was a Swedish poet .
Olivier Elzéar Mathieu ( 24 December 1853 -- 26 October 1929 ) was a Canadian Roman Catholic priest , academic , and Archbishop of Regina .
Emile Vandervelde ( also Émile ; 25 January 1866 -- 27 December 1938 ) was a Belgian statesman .
Isaac de Caus ( 1590 - -1648 ) was a French landscaper and architect .
August Lindberg ( born 1885 , Älvkarleby , d. 1966 ) was a Swedish trade union organizer .
José Tous Soto ( October 2 , 1874 -- 1933 ) was a Puerto Rican politician and former Senator and Representative .
Gonzalo Fernández de Traba ( died 1160 ) was a Galician nobleman and the leader of the House of Traba .
John Lister Illingworth Fennell ( 1918 - -1992 ) was a British historian of medieval Russian history and of Russian literature .
Elizabeth Dickson or Elizabeth Dalzac ( -- 30 April 1862 ) was a British woman who raised the British public profile of the Christian white slaves held in north Africa by the Barbary Slave Trade .
Adolf Behne ( 13 July 1885 -- 22 August 1948 ) was a critic , art historian , architectural writer , and artistic activist .
Sir Richard Mompesson ( died 1627 ) , of Mompesson House , Cathedral Close , Salisbury , Wiltshire , was a Member ( MP ) of the Parliament of England for Devizes in 1593 .

Iba Hideaki ( 1648 -- 1717 ) was a famed swordsman during the Edo period ( 17th century ) of Japan .
Fitzherbert Adams D.D. ( 1651 -- 17 June 1719 ) was a man of learning , and benefactor of the University of Oxford .
Dessaline Harris ( 1 October 1895 - 29 March 1966 ) was a Liberian jurist and a member of the Supreme Court of Liberia .
John Russell , 4th Duke of Bedford KG PC FRS ( 30 September 1710 -- 5 January 1771 ) was an 18th - century British statesman .
Robert Henry Scott FRS ( 28 January 1833 -- 18 June 1916 ) was an Irish meteorologist , who was president of the Royal Meteorological Society .
Faheem Hussain , DPhil ( 31 July 1942 -- 29 September 2009 ) , was a Pakistani theoretical physicist and a professor of physics at the Lahore University of Management Sciences ( LUMS ) .
Adolf Samassa de Gesztőcz ( 13 April 1867 , Zlaté Moravce -- 31 January 1929 ) was a Hungarian politician , who served as Interior Minister for few days in 1919 .
Ezmel de Ablitas ( died 1342 ) , `` the rich Jew of Ablitas '' , had business relations with the King of Navarre and Aragon .
Mufazzal Haider Chaudhury ( Bengali : মোফাজ্জল হায়দার চৌধুরী ; 22 July 1926 -- 14 December 1971 ) was a prominent Bengali essayist , prized scholar of Bengali literature , educator and linguist of the Bengali language .
Bernd Eisenfeld ( 9 January 1941 -- 12 June 2010 ) , also known by the pseudonym Fred Werner , was an opponent of the East German dictatorship who became a writer and an historian .
Sam Pata Emani Tagelagi ( 29 December 1935 -- 10 September 2011 ) was a Niuean politician and elder .
Hugh Wigan ( fl . 1386 - 1407 ) of Shrewsbury and Hereford , was an English politician .
Gvido Birolla ( 12 June 1881 -- 29 May 1963 ) was a Slovene painter , illustrator and caricaturist , known for his political caricatures published in satirical newspapers of the time and his book illustrations .
Netrabahadur Thapa VC ( Nepali : नेत्रबहादुर थापा 8 January 1916 -- 26 June 1944 ) was a Nepalese Gurkha recipient of the Victoria Cross , the highest and most prestigious award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to British and Commonwealth forces .
Hafliði Másson ( died 1130 ) was an Icelandic goði and chieftain in the eleventh to twelfth centuries .
Émile Deville ( 25 January 1824 -- 8 January 1853 ) was a French physician , naturalist and taxidermist .
Leonard R. Lipowicz ( June 10 , 1895 -- February 1981 ) was an American lawyer and politician from New York .

Romain - Octave Pelletier I ( sometimes spelled Peltier ) ( 9 September 1843 -- 4 March 1927 ) was a Canadian organist , pianist , composer , writer on music , and music educator .
Wynne Godley ( 2 September 1926 -- 13 May 2010 ) was an economist famous for his pessimism toward the British economy and his criticism of the British government .
Mickey Duff ( 7 June 1929 -- 22 March 2014 ) , was a Polish - born British boxer , manager and promoter .
Padovanino or Varotari Alessandro Leone ( 4 April 1588 -- 20 July 1649 ) , also commonly known as Il Padovanino , was an Italian painter of the late - Mannerist and early - Baroque Venetian school , best known for having mentored Pietro Liberi , Giulio Carpioni , and Bartolommeo Scaligero .
Emily Charlotte Talbot ( 1 August 1840 -- 21 September 1918 ) was an heiress and industrialist of South Wales , the daughter of Christopher Rice Mansel Talbot .
Geoffrey Colin Guy CMG , CVO , OBE ( 4 November 1921 -- 1 December 2006 ) was the last Commissioner and the first Administrator of the Turks and Caicos from 1958 to 1959 and 1959 to 1965 respectively .

Eric Irons OBE ( 1921 - -2007 ) was Britains first black magistrate and a campaigner for equal rights .
The Martyrs of Gorkum ( Dutch : Martelaren van Gorcum ) were a group of 19 Dutch Catholic clerics and friars who were hanged on 9 July 1572 in the town of Brielle ( or Den Briel ) during the 16th century religious wars in the Low Countries by the Calvinists .
René Vignaud ( 19 January 1893 -- October 1969 ) was a French runner .

Guru Chandrasekharan ( 1916 - -1998 ) was an Indian classical dancer , choreographer and instructor of Kathakali .

Ciarán Ó Con Cheanainn ( 12 July 1981 - 4 February 2009 ) Irish scholar , teacher and youngest winner of the Corn Uí Riada .

Anatjari Tjakamarra ( c. 1930 - -1992 ) was a Central Australian Aboriginal artist who was part of the Papunya Tula art movement .
Günther Schifter ( 23 December 1923 -- 11 August 2008 ) was an Austrian journalist , radio presenter and record collector .
Joseph ben Judah ibn Aknin ( c. 1150 -- c. 1220 ) was a Jewish writer of numerous treatises , mostly on the Mishnah and the Talmud .

Jan Hambourg ( 27 August 1882 --29 September 1947 ) was a Russian violinist , a member of a famous musical family , who made his career in Europe during the early 20th century .

John Guillermin ( 11 November 1925 -- 27 September 2015 ) was a British film director , writer , and producer who was most active in big budget , action adventure films throughout his lengthy career .

Jim Loriot ( 16 January 1879 -- 18 August 1951 ) was a former Australian rules footballer who played with Carlton in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .

Hugh Cortez Jordan ( 1921 -- 8 September 1982 ) was a Test cricket umpire between 1953 and 1974 .
William Menzies Tweedie ( 1826 - -1878 ) was a Scottish portrait - painter .
Scipione Gonzaga ( 11 November 1542 -- 11 January 1593 ) was an Italian cardinal .
Bartholomew II Ghisi ( Italian : Bartolommeo Ghisi ; died 1341 ) was a Latin feudal lord in medieval Greece , lord of Tinos and Mykonos , Triarch of Negroponte and Grand Constable of the Principality of Achaea .
Alf Kjellin ( 28 February 1920 -- 5 April 1988 ) was a Swedish film actor and director , who also appeared on some television shows .
Baruch Hirson ( 10 December 1921 -- 3 October 1999 ) was a South African political activist and historian .
Sir William Glynne , 2nd Baronet ( 17 May 1663 -- 3 September 1721 ) was a Welsh lawyer and politician .
Sir Henry Finch ( died 1625 ) was an English lawyer and politician , created serjeant - at - law and knighted , and remembered as a legal writer .
John Tuson Bennett ( 12 November 1937 , Horsham , Victoria -- 22 July 2013 ) was a solicitor and president of the Australian Civil Liberties Union , who was most notable for being a leader in the Holocaust denial movement in Australia .
Cai Pei ( Chinese : 蔡培 ; pinyin : Cài Péi ; Wade -- Giles : Ts'ai P'ei ; Hepburn : Sai Bai ; 1884 -- 1960 ) was a diplomat and politician in the pre - war Republic of China .
Rudolf John Gorsleben ( 16 March 1883 -- 23 August 1930 ) was a German Ariosophist , Armanist ( practitioner of the Armanen runes ) , journal editor and playwright .
Carol Kreeger Davidson ( 17 May 1929 - 16 June 2014 ) was an American sculptor known for her Postminimalist style and technique of bending , folding , and bolting material rather than welding .
Ulpiano Díaz ( 1900 - -1990 ) was a Cuban timbalero .
George Fillmore Swain ( 2 March 1857 , San Francisco , California - 1 July 1931 ) was a civil engineer from the USA .
Ernst Carl Theodor Zincke ( 19 May 1843 -- 17 March 1928 ) was a German chemist and the academic adviser of Otto Hahn .
Walter Russell Hall ( 22 February 1831 -- 13 October 1911 ) was an Australian businessman and benefactor .
Jampa Tsering died in a car crash in 1997 .
Emma Henry ( date of birth unknown - 1986 ) was a Filipino police officer whose exploits were the subject of two Filipino film biopics wherein she starred as herself .
Maureen Watson , also known as Aunty Maureen ( 9 November 1931 -- 4 January 2009 ) was an avid supporter of Aboriginal rights in Australia , as well as a world renowned actor , vocalist , writer , musician and storyteller .
Joshua Janavel , also written Giosuè Gianavello ( 1617 -- 5 March 1690 ) was an Italian condottiero and defender of the Waldensian Church .
R. D. Hilton Smith ( 1903 - -1974 ) has been described as ... a British librarian ( of London ) and once head of the Toronto Public Library , came to Victoria in the early 1950s where he established Adelphi Books .
Pierre - Émile Launois ( 24 July 1856 -- 18 March 1914 ) was a French physician born in Moiremont , a commune in the department of Marne .
Walter Whitford ( ca . 1581 - -1647 ) was a seventeenth - century Scottish minister , prelate and Royalist .
Charles Laurence ( 10 January 1931 -- 13 July 2013 ) was an actor and playwright who worked in films and television .
Alexander Viggo Jensen ( 22 June 1874 - 2 November 1930 ) was a Danish weightlifter , shooter , gymnast , and athlete .
Edgar Sanabria Arcia ( Spanish pronunciation : ( ˈeðɣar saˈnaβɾja ) ; 3 October 1911 -- 24 April 1989 ) was a Venezuelan lawyer , diplomat , and politician .
Robert Barclay ( 23 December 1648 -- 3 October 1690 ) was a Scottish Quaker , one of the most eminent writers belonging to the Religious Society of Friends and a member of the Clan Barclay .
Volker Straus ( b. July 5 , 1936 in Speyer , Germany -- d. April 21 , 2002 in Bilthoven , Netherlands ) was one of the foremost Tonmeisters of the twentieth century .
Alfred Edward Taylor ( 22 December 1869 -- 31 October 1945 ) was a British idealist philosopher most famous for his contributions to the philosophy of idealism in his writings on metaphysics , the philosophy of religion , moral philosophy , and the scholarship of Plato .
Lance Corporal Johnson Paudash MM ( 29 January 1875 -- 26 October 1959 ) was an acclaimed Canadian sniper during the First World War .
Roger Mortimer , 1st Baron Mortimer , of Wigmore ( 1231 -- 30 October 1282 ) , was a famous and honoured knight from Wigmore Castle in Herefordshire .
Leonard M. Rieser ( 18 May 1922 -- 15 December 1998 ) was an American physicist who worked on the Manhattan Project and later for nuclear disarmament .
Stephen William White ( 16 July 1840 -- October 1914 ) was the secretary of the Northern Central Railway as well as a number of other Pennsylvanian railway companies until his retirement in 1910 .
Shamsul Huda Bihari ( S. H. Bihari ) ( d. 1987 ) was an Indian songwriter and poet whose work was widely recorded and used in Bollywood movies during the latter half of the 20th century .
Lansana Diané ( died 1985 ) was a general and a minister in the cabinet of Ahmed Sekou Touré , President of Guinea during the First Republic ( 1958 - -1984 ) .
Lőrinc Wathay ( ? - 1573 ) was a Hungarian nobleman and castellan of Csesznek .
Arthur Adamson ( 10 January 1882 -- 16 July 1966 ) was an Australian rules football player who played 28 games and scored no goals for the South Melbourne Football Club in the 1902 and 1903 seasons .
Yuranigh ( approx . 1820 -- April 1850 ) was an Australian Indigenous guide and stockman .
Liu Jiyuan ( 劉繼元 ) ( died in 992 ) , was the last ruler of ancient China 's Northern Han kingdom in its Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms period .
Marcus Pomponius Maecius Probus ( ca 195 -- aft . 228 ) was a Consul in 228 .
Prince Olayiwola Fatai Olagunju , known better as Fatai Rolling Dollar ( 22 July 1927 -- 12 June 2013 ) , was a Nigerian musician , described by the BBC as a `` nationally celebrated performer . ''
Hans Jørgensen ( 1886 - -1954 ) was the founder of Newar studies in the west .
Very Reverend Alexander Carlyle DD FRSE ( 26 January 1722 - -28 August 1805 ) was a Scottish church leader , and autobiographer .
Dorothea Bennett ( December 27 , 1929 in Honolulu -- August 16 , 1990 in Houston ) was a geneticist , known for the genetics of early mammalian development and for research into mammalian sperm surface structures and their role in fertilization and spermatogenesis .
Heonjong of Goryeo ( 1 August 1084 - 6 November 1097 ) ( r. 1094 - -1095 ) was the fourteenth monarch of the Goryeo dynasty of Korea .
Jean - Baptiste Lagimodière ( 25 December 1778 in Chambly , Quebec -- 7 September 1855 ) was a French Canadian trapper employed in the fur trade by the Hudson 's Bay Company in Rupert 's Land .
František Maxián ( 9 November 1907 -- 18 January 1971 ) was a Czech pianist and music educator .
Alan A. Freeman ( 27 September 1920 -- 15 March 1985 ) was an English record producer , remembered for being Petula Clark 's producer from 1949 until 1963 , when his role was taken over by Tony Hatch .
Saint - Louis Blaise ( 1956 - -1995 ) , or St. Louis Blaise , is a Haitian painter .
Alf - Jørgen Aas ( 5 July 1915 - 20 August 1981 ) was a Norwegian painter and art instructor .
Charles Battell Loomis ( 1861 - -1911 ) was an American author , born in Brooklyn , New York , and educated at the Polytechnic Institute there .
Charles Buxton Going ( April 4 , 1863 - 1952 in France ) was an American engineer , author , and editor .
Francis Legge ( c.1719 - 1783 ) , was a British military officer and colonial official in Nova Scotia during the 18th century .
Thomas Sedgwick ( Segiswycke ) ( died 1573 in a Yorkshire prison ) was an English Roman Catholic theologian .
Rabbi Nachman Shlomo Greenspan ( Hebrew : נחמן שלמה גרינשפן‎ ; 1878 - -August 1961 ) was an Talmudic scholar , rosh yeshiva of Etz Chaim in London , and an author of a number of works about the Torah .
Giovanni dalle Carceri ( died 1358 ) was a Lord of Euboea .
Swami Vishnu Tirtha ( ? --1969 ) , also known as Munilal Swami , was a sannyasin , writer , and guru with a prominent place in the Shaktipat tradition of Siddhayoga .
Bartholomew de Badlesmere , 1st Baron Badlesmere ( 18 August 1275 -- 14 April 1322 ) , English soldier , diplomat , Member of Parliament , landowner and nobleman , was the son and heir of Sir Gunselin de Badlesmere ( died circa 1301 ) and Joan FitzBernard .
Bertha of Sulzbach ( 1110s -- August 29 , 1159 ) was the first wife and Empress of Byzantine Emperor Manuel I Comnenus .
Stephen of La Ferté was Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem from 1128 until his death in 1130 .
Asa Finley ( 1788 - -1853 ) was a politician and judge in Missouri .
David Askevold ( 30 March 1940 -- 23 January 2008 ) was an experimental Canadian artist who lived in Nova Scotia .
Claes van Heussen ( 1598 -- 1633 , Haarlem ) , was a Dutch Golden Age still life painter who died young .
Pater Sigbert Wagener ( OFMCap ) ( 29 October 1919 , Krefeld as Karl Emil Wagener-13 April 2004 ) was a German Capuchin priest , a teacher , a scientist and naturalist especially interested in entomology .
Harold Truscott ( 23 August 1914 -- 7 October 1992 ) was a British composer , pianist , broadcaster and writer on music .
Schiøler Linck born Valdemar Schiøler Linck ( 26 October 1878 -- 6 September 1952 ) , was a Danish stage and film actor .
Sir John Moore Caldicott KBE , CMG ( 12 February 1900 -- 31 January 1986 ) was a Rhodesian government minister .
Énemond Massé ( 1575 -- 12 May 1646 ) was a French Jesuit missionary , one of the first Jesuits sent to New France .
Ellen Cannon Reed ( 21 March 1943 -- 7 October 2003 ) was the most widely known priestess of the Isian Tradition of Witchcraft .
Anna Kavan ( born Helen Emily Woods ; 10 April 1901 -- 5 December 1968 ) was a British novelist , short story writer and painter .
Jerzy Rudlicki ( 14 March 1893 - 18 August 1977 ) was a Polish Pilot and Aerospace Engineer .
Sir John Alexander Hammerton ( born 27 February 1871 in Alexandria , Scotland ; died 12 May 1949 in London ) is described by the Dictionary of National Biography as `` the most successful creator of large - scale works of reference that Britain has known '' .
Sir Francis Pettit Smith ( 1808 -- 12 February 1874 ) was an English inventor and , along with John Ericsson , one of the inventors of the screw propeller .
William Ormston Backhouse ( 1885 -- 1962 ) was an agriculturalist and geneticist , and a member of the Backhouse family of County Durham in England , several generations of which were influential in the development of horticulture .
Asa Danforth Jr. ( June 29 , 1768 -- c. 1821 ) was one of the first citizens of Onondaga County , New York , when he arrived there with his father , Asa Danforth in 1788 .
Alexander Doniphan Wallace ( 21 August 1905 Hampton , Virginia , USA -- 16 October 1985 New Orleans , USA ) was an American mathematician who introduced proximity spaces .
James Gibb Stuart ( 30 August 1920 -- 23 September 2013 ) was a financial author , owner of Ossian Publishers , and chairman of the Scottish Pure Water Association .
Jean Erdman , Baron Dieskau or Jean - Armand Dieskau , Baron de Dieskau or Ludwig August von Dieskau ( 1701 Saxony -- 8 September 1767 Surenne ) was a German - born soldier remembered mostly as a French general and commander in America for a part of the French and Indian War .
Leif Solberg ( 18 November 1914 -- 25 January 2016 ) was a Norwegian classical composer and organist .
Justice Chan Htoon ( ချန်ထွန်း , pronounced : ( tɕʰáɴ tʰʊ́ɴ ) ; 23 April 1906 -- 16 May 1988 ) was Attorney General and Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of Burma , and the architect of the first constitution of Burma in 1947 .
Jack Tinker ( 15 February 1938 -- 28 October 1996 ) was an English theatre critic .
Rachel Yanait Ben - Zvi ( Hebrew : רחל ינאית בן - צבי‎‎ ; 1886 -- 16 November 1979 ) was an Israeli author and educator , and a leading Labor Zionist .
Arild Eik ( 16 September 1943 -- 6 March 2009 ) was a Norwegian development aid worker and diplomat .
João Esteves da Veiga de Nápoles ( 1397 - -1461 ) was a Portuguese nobleman and Minister - Counselor , the eldest ( and probably only ) son of Leonardo Esteves de Nápoles and his wife Margarida Anes Afonso .
Samuel Lover ( 24 February 1797 -- 6 July 1868 ) was an Irish songwriter , composer , novelist , and a painter of portraits , chiefly miniatures .
Henry Mellish FRGS , CB ( 31 October 1856 -- 1927 ) was known for his participation in competitive rifle shooting and meteorology .
Lunsford Lane ( May 30 , 1803 -- June 1879 ) was an African - American slave and entrepreneur from North Carolina who bought freedom for himself and his family .
Alessandro Orologio ( also Alexander Horologius ) ( c. 1550 - -1633 ) was an Italian composer and instrumentalist , who lived in German lands .
Jessica Dismorr ( 3 March 1885 -- 29 August 1939 ) was an English painter and illustrator and one of only two women members of the Vorticist movement .
Lewis Temple ( 22 October 1800 -- 18 May 1854 ) was an American blacksmith , abolitionist , and inventor .
On 14 May 1920 , Harold Ross Eycott - Martin -- mistakenly characterized as still an RAF officer -- was reported as residing at 9 Trebovir Road , Earls Court , London , as well as the Maiden Head Hotel , Uckfield , Sussex .
Ramdas Gandhi ( 1897 -- April 14 , 1969 ) was the third son of Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi .
Xiao Wangdong ( Chinese : 肖望东 ; Wade -- Giles : Hsiao Wang - tung ; August 1910 -- 11 May 1989 ) was a Chinese Communist revolutionary and a lieutenant general of the People 's Liberation Army ( PLA ) .
Hugh Fraser , 1st Baron Fraser of Allander ( 15 January 1903 -- 6 November 1966 ) was the grandson of Hugh Fraser I , and the father of Sir Hugh Fraser , 2nd Baronet .
Sapiah was the leader of the Southern Ute tribe from 1880 until his death in 1936 .
Hugh Sexey ( 1556 - -1619 ) was born near Bruton , Somerset and attended Bruton Grammar School .
Cromwell Everson ( 28 September 1925 -- 11 June 1991 ) was primarily known as a composer during his lifetime .
Srul Bronshtein ( Yiddish : סראָל בראָנשטײן‎ ; c. 1913 - -1943 ) was a Romanian and Soviet Yiddish - language poet .
William Theobald ( 1829 -- 31 March 1908 ) was a malacologist and naturalist on the staff of the Geological Survey of India in Burma .
Elmar Muuk ( 26 December 1901 -- 20 November 1941 ) was an Estonian linguist and author of a number of dictionaries and textbooks of the Estonian language , and was , together with Mihkel Veske and Johannes Aavik , responsible for development of Estonian as a modern European language .
Sir John Morphett ( 4 May 1809 -- 7 November 1892 ) was a South Australian pioneer , landowner and politician .
Shimon Fritz Bodenheimer ( Hebrew שמעון פריץ בודנהיימר ) ( June 6 , 1897 - October 4 , 1959 ) was an Israeli entomologist and zoologist .
Samuel J. Hamrick ( 1929 - -2008 ) was an American spy novelist , who often used the pen name W. T. Tyler .
Samuel Wyllys ( 1739 - 1823 ) was an American military officer and a Connecticut politician .
Admiral Eduard von Capelle ( 10 October 1855 -- 23 February 1931 ) was a German Imperial Navy officer from Celle .
Robert Ditter ( 23 January 1924 , Lauda , Baden − 24 January 2007 , Schramberg ) was principal of the Gymnasium Schramberg from 1964 to 1988 .
St. John Welles Lucas - Lucas , commonly known as St. John Lucas , ( 1879 - -1934 ) was an English poet known for his anthologies of verse .
Martin Luther Stoever ( born in Germantown , Pennsylvania , 17 February 1820 ; died there , 22 July 1870 ) was a United States Lutheran educator and writer .
Wilhelm Matthias Naeff ( 19 February 1802 -- 21 January 1881 ) was a Swiss politician and one of the seven initial members of the Swiss Federal Council ( 1848 - -1875 ) .
James Arthur Harris ( 1880 - 1930 ) was a botanist and biometrician , known for the Benedict - Harris equations , He was the Head of the Department of Botany at the University of Minnesota from 1924 to 1930 .
John Thewlis senior ( 30 June 1828 -- 29 December 1899 ) was an English first - class cricketer , who played in forty four matches for Yorkshire County Cricket Club , and fifty six first - class matches in all between 1862 and 1875 .
Paul de Schlözer or Paweł Schlözer ( 1841 or 1842 -- 1898 ) was a Polish pianist and teacher of German descent .
Xu Shouhui ( simplified Chinese : 徐寿辉 ; traditional Chinese : 徐壽輝 ; pinyin : Xú Shòuhuī ; Wade -- Giles : Hsü Shou - hui ) ( died 1360 ) was a 14th - century Chinese rebel leader who proclaimed himself emperor during the late Mongol Yuan Dynasty period .
